{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513216","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513216"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:06:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:06:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12052"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12052","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12052"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.06,0.46,0.42,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4618"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44734"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4618","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4618"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12052"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29608"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"45"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1493"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6997"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7034"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34258"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44734","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/44734"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 23-year-old woman was driving along a busy highway in the rain, when a driver lost control of their vehicle and collided with her vehicle. It was estimated that the crash occurred at 100km/hr. The woman was trapped in her vehicle unconscious until rescue crews retrieved her and rushed her to the nearest trauma centre. She was GCS 3 at the scene. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter significant resuscitation in the trauma bay, the woman was admitted to the trauma unit in an unconscious state with a significant traumatic brain injury from intracranial haemorrhage and numerous skeletal fractures. Her GCS remained at 3 upon arrival to the hospital. Whilst on the trauma unit, the women remained unconscious for 10 days.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter 12 weeks on the trauma ward allowing her skeletal injuries to heal, she was moved to a rehabilitation facility, at which the clinicians determined that her abbreviated Westmead post-traumatic amnesia (PTA) scale score was 5.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following represents the severity of this woman\u0027s traumatic brain injury?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Mild","Moderate","Severe","Very severe","Undeterminable"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis woman has suffered a significant traumatic brain injury (TBI) from her motor vehicle accident. To determine the severity of her TBI, there are classification criteria used by clinicians that incorporates a number of factors, such as:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGCS at the scene of the accident\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELength of time that the patient lost consciousness\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPost-traumatic amnesia length of time\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEmergence from PTA is determined by 3 consecutive days with a Westmead score \u0026gt;12\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EImaging of the brain\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHence, the following classifications have these features:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMild TBI:\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGCS 13-15\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELoss of consciousness \u0026lt;30mins\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPTA 0-1 days\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENormal brain imaging\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EModerate TBI:\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGCS 9-12\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELoss of consciousness \u0026gt;30mins but \u0026lt;24hr\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPTA \u0026gt;1 but \u0026lt;7 days\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENormal or abnormal brain imaging\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESevere TBI:\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGCS \u0026lt;9\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELoss of consciousness \u0026gt;24hr\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPTA \u0026gt;7 days\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENormal or abnormal brain imaging\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEvidently this woman has suffered a \u003Cstrong\u003Esevere \u003C/strong\u003ETBI.\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003ENumerous studies have identified that GCS specifically used as a means of determining the severity of the TBI will also aid in prognostication of the ABI. The mortality rates of TBI increase with the extent of the injury to the brain:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMild TBI\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with a mortality of 0.1%\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EModerate TBI \u003C/strong\u003Eis associated with a mortality of 10%\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESevere TBI \u003C/strong\u003Eis associated with a mortality of 40%\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["TBI severity is classified into mild, moderate and severe and may aid in predicting outcomes for the patient long term"],"references":["O\u0027Neil ME, Carlson K, Storzbach D, et al. Complications of Mild Traumatic Brain Injury in Veterans and Military Personnel: A Systematic Review [Internet]. Washington (DC): Department of Veterans Affairs (US); 2013 Jan. Table A-1, Classification of TBI Severity. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK189784/table/appc.t1/","Mena JH, Sanchez AI, Rubiano AM, et al. Effect of the modified Glasgow Coma Scale score criteria for mild traumatic brain injury on mortality prediction: comparing classic and modified Glasgow Coma Scale score model scores of 13. J Trauma. 2011 Nov;71(5):1185-92; discussion 1193.","classification of TBI severity: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK189784/table/appc.t1/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29608"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12052"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29608","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/29608"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-04-28T08:51:25+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-20T15:33:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4618"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44734"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"32","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/32"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurosurgery","synonyms":null,"descr